ation from the lists of therapies — relegating them to the great bazaar of medical fraud. ... Medical charlatans do not base their claims on scientific proof but, quite to the contrary, on peremptory assertions — the kind of assertions that they challenge when they come out of the mouths of those who defend “real” medicine. |archive-date=2020-09-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200909003118/https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache%3ACvvF1-YT9pYJ%3Awww.fk.unair.ac.id%2Fpdfiles%2Febook%2FHealing%2520or%2520Stealing.%2520Medical%2520Charlatans%2520in%2520the%2520New%2520Age.pdf+&hl=en&gl=uk&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESiaAqB8ye_YQOHTE0a4yshe-xhyTZH1Nh6lK8SojGzl2-xnF9vAL8ZRKaS851sVJmoZu4DTENhfAG1Z2r8C4nquVSHVFRp6d8itswdubevY50t02ct-s5BfbJmFZ74IP9OKCAdN&sig=AHIEtbQfXuB0dLigp4k18tHB0r2WKppaUA |dead-url=no }}</ref>」，
